ish <i>blac</i> also meant ‘pale, wan’, a reflex of Old English <i>blāc</i> ‘pale, white’ with a shortened vowel. Compare   Blatch   and   Blick  . With rare exceptions it is impossible to disambiguate these antithetical senses in Middle English surnames. The same difficulty arises with   Blake   and   Block  .","Scottish: in Gaelic-speaking areas this name was adopted as a translation of the epithet <i>dubh</i> ‘dark, black-(haired)’, or of various other names based on Gaelic <i>dubh</i> ‘black’, see   Duff  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames directly or indirectly derived from the adjective meaning ‘black, dark’, for example German and Jewish   Schwarz   and Slavic surnames beginning with <i>Čern-</i>, <i>Chern-</i> (see   Chern   and   Cherne  ), <i>Chorn-</i>, <i>Crn-</i> or <i>Czern-</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":1,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When John Blackett was born in 1381, in Icomb, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Blackett, was 36 and his mother, Margaret de Hastings, was 28. He married Margaret Beaupyne in 1409, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 24 June 1430, in England, at the age of 49, and was buried in Icomb, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1381–24 June 1430":"1381–24. juuni 1430","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1381–1430":"1381–1430","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1412–1442